title: For Trade:  AK47 drum 75 round new in box
postcontent:
This is an original Chinese drum that fits any AK style rifle that accepts double stack magazines. You simply open the door, load 75 rounds of ammo, close the door and wind up the spring.

These are great for storing loaded ammo supplies. Load it, don't wind it until you need it. The spring does NOT weaken even during long term storage!

This drum attaches to the rifle exactly like a normal clip. No alterations to the rifle are required. Simply drop in all 75 rounds of ammo, close the cover, wind up the spring, and you are ready to fire. A wind-up drum is a great way to store a loaded magazine long-term without the worry of a compressed spring loosing its ability to deliver enough push to empty a magazine. With the drum, you don't wind up the spring until you are ready to use the drum.

Will consider trades

title: For Sale:  NJ Legal Alexander Arms Sabre Defense AR15 5.45x39
postcontent:
Arsenal. Alexander Arms / Sabre Defense have developed many special weapons for the US army, including the 6.5 Grendel AR 15 platform which the US Army uses for sniping in Iraq and Afghanistan, they also developed the .50 Beowulf which the Army uses to stop suicide bombers ad their vehicles in Iraq and Afghanistan.

They developed the .21 Genghis in response to Special Forces request for a weapon chambered in 5.45x39. 5.45x39 is the round fired by the AK 74 rifle. This was the standard rifle of the Soviet Union, that is what they carried during their invasion of Afghanistan and it is the preferred cartridge of the Afghan Muja rebels even to this day. It is also used by the Iraqi and Afghan armies and is the most plentiful round found in the Middle East. Special forces wanted a reliable weapon which they could use in the field without having the carry a lot of ammo for it. The trouble with 5.56 nato was no opposing forces carried it in their rifles, so the US forces had to carry their ammo with them, once they ran out they either needed resupply or they were done for. In the mountains of Afghanistan resupply is not always a feasible alternative. However, there was plenty of 5.45x39 ammo lying around on the dead Taliban fighters, so the US special forces could always get that ammo. That is why Alexander Arms developed the AR in that cartridge. They are the only ones in the world to make an AR 15 rifle in that cartridge.

You are bidding on a full rifle which was made by Alexander Arms in 5.45x39, it is not just an upper on a standard receiver, the whole rifle came from Alexander Arms, as the receiver markings with testify. They started with a Rock River M4 Operator and converted it to 5.45x39. The advantage of the caliber in the US is that the market is awash with surplus Russian ammo, even true AP ammo. You can still buy this ammo for $100 per 1080 rounds, no other powerful rifle ammo is available in this price range. The ammo also has plenty of choices to select when buying, including the cheapest which is real AP steel core Russian surplus bullets, unlike the US made M855 Penetrators in 5.56 which only have a steel tip, the Russian AP ammo is truly AP, and will go through even Level IV vests with armor plates. The rifle does not have a flash hider because it was made to be mated with a silencer, since I live in the People’s Republic of Illinois and Obamas home district, no silencers are allowed here so nothing was ever mounted on the muzzle. However, a muzzle break can be mounted on the cheap by any competent gunsmith. The rifle also comes with factory box and papers, the box is a reinforced metal combination case which is extremely heavy and sturdy.

title: For Sale:  schmitt rubin k31 swiss7.5x55 sale pending
postcontent:
The world renowned Swiss, Karabiner Model 31 or also known in collector slang as the Swiss Schmidt-Rubin K31 was adopted in 1933 and stayed in service until 1958. Based on a long lineage of straight pull bolt action rifles, beginning with the Schmidt-Rubin Model 1889. Rubin designed the bullet that was combined with Schmidt's straight pull bolt rifle. 

A very accurate, detachable magazine fed rifle with a very unique straight pull bolt that allowed the soldier to quickly chamber rounds by pulling straight back on the bolt and then slamming it forward. Very revolutionary engineering in a battle rifle for the late 1800's. Because of the straight pull bolt technology the Swiss soldier did not have to raise up (exposing themselves to enemy fire) and chamber a round, like a standard turn-bolt rifle. 
this rifle is the most accurate surplus rifle i have shot.
 it is in excellent shape, it has the typical scratches and dings in the stock you see in these rifles.
 the bluing is in excellent shape also.
 bore is mirror and crown is excellent.
 if you want one of the most accurate surplus rifles there is,the swiss engineering of these rifles are amazing.

title: Want To Buy:  Mosin-Nagant
postcontent:
I am looking to purchase a Mosin-Nagant. I am looking for an 1891 or 1891/30. I would be interested in any of these variations. I do not want any variation of the Mosin-Nagant carbine. 

Criteria: I would like one that has all matching numbers and all original equipment that is usually included with a Mosin-Nagant. I am still open to rifles that have mixed numbers but I won't pay as much. I am looking for something that is able to shoot accurate and has little to no damage with no missing parts. I do not want a rifle that has been cut down or modified that can not be reversed. I want to be able to see the rifle in person before the actual purchase of the rifle.

If you are going to offer to sell me your Mosin-Nagant please include the year it was manufactured and the brand if possible, the model of the rifle, how much if any damage the rifle has, what is included, and how much you want. Please let me know if it does not meet any of the criteria listed above. I would also like recent pictures of the rifle. Depending on the condition of the rifle and what is included I am prepared to pay up to $300 possibly more if I think it is worth it.

I am willing to drive 1 hour from my location to look at a rifle. If you are a serious seller and the deal is good enough I might drive further. I am also able to drive to the Richmond, Indiana are if you are willing to ship the rifle to my local gun shop.

Hello there!
I'm selling my beloved FNS-9, moving up my inventory from 9mm to .45acp.
Initially, I was in the market to buy a Glock 19 however, I found the FNS9 to have offered more while still having an optimal trigger that is often difficult to replicate Glock's.
It's a very ergonomic pistol for shooters with small hands, such as myself, and there is also interchangeable back-strap for those with larger hands.
1911 style grip angle with thumb safety as well, not very common on striker fired pistols; this is if you choose to use it, I was going to carry this in condition 1, however I lacked a holster to even do so.
I'm parting ways now to save on the cost of this recent ammo fiasco and just strictly staying with .45acp

It shoots very accurate with no malfunctions. Being the 2013 Golden Bullseye Award Winner in the pistols category; I didn't expect any less.

Here's what you get
-FNS-9, LNIB condition, only 50 rounds through it of West Coast Armory white box.
*matte stainless finish, the rarer of the two avaliable options.
*comes with 3 high capacity magazines, 17 round
*slim and thick backstraps
*comes with Trijicon night sights!
*original box and papers/ lock

The only trades I'm open to are a Baby Eagle in 45ACP, SIG P220 SAO, or Officer (4") 1911's
Looking especially for a Springfield Champion Operator.
Cash +/- on mine or your part.

MORE PICTURES HERE:
http://s77.photobucket.com/albums/j46/maikelldwong/FNS-9mm/
I'm asking for $650
